SIMPLE: earnest
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Earnest
<hw>Ear"nest</hw> <pr>(⟦etil⟧r"n⟦ecr⟧st)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[AS.
<ets>eornost</ets>, <ets>eornest</ets>; akin to OHG. <ets>ernust</ets>,
G. <ets>ernst</ets>; cf. Icel. <ets>orrosta</ets> battle, perh. akin to
Gr. <grk>'orny`nai</grk> to excite, L. <ets>oriri</ets> to rise.]</ety>
<def>Seriousness; reality; fixed determination; eagerness;
intentness.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Take heed that this jest do not one day turn to
<qex>earnest</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Sir P. Sidney.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And given in <qex>earnest</qex> what I begged in jest.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>In earnest</b></col>, <cd>serious; seriously; not in
jest; earnestly.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Earnest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Earnest
<hw>Ear"nest</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Ardent in the pursuit
of an object; eager to obtain or do; zealous with sincerity; with hearty
endeavor; heartfelt; fervent; hearty; -- used in a good sense; <as>as,
<ex>earnest</ex> prayers</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>An <qex>earnest</qex> advocate to plead for him.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Intent; fixed closely; <as>as, <ex>earnest</ex>
attention</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Serious; important.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They whom <qex>earnest</qex> lets do often hinder.</q>
<rj><qau>Hooker.</qau></rj></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Eager; warm; zealous; ardent; animated;
importunate; fervent; sincere; serious; hearty; urgent. See
<er>Eager</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Earnest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Earnest
<hw>Ear"nest</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To use in earnest.</def>
<mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To <qex>earnest</qex> them [our arms] with men.</q>
<rj><qau>Pastor Fido (1602).</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Earnest</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Earnest
<hw>Ear"nest</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[Prob. corrupted fr. F.
<ets>arrhes</ets>, L. <ets>arra</ets>, <ets>arrha</ets>,
<ets>arrhabo</ets>, Gr. <grk>'arrabw`n</grk>, of Semitic origin, cf.
Heb. <ets>⟦emac⟧r⟦amac⟧v⟦omac⟧n</ets>; or perh. fr. W. <ets>ernes</ets>,
akin to Gael. <ets>earlas</ets>, perh. fr. L. <ets>arra</ets>. Cf.
<er>Arles</er>, <er>Earles penny</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Something
given, or a part paid beforehand, as a pledge; pledge; handsel; a token
of what is to come.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who hath also sealed us, and given the <qex>earnest</qex> of the
Spirit in our hearts.</q> <rj><qau>2 Cor. i. 22.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>And from his coffers⟦br⟧
Received the golden <qex>earnest</qex> of our death.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <fld>(Law)</fld> <def>Something of value given by the
buyer to the seller, by way of token or pledge, to bind the bargain and
prove the sale.</def> <rj><au>Kent. Ayliffe. Benjamin.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Earnest money</b></col> <fld>(Law)</fld>, <cd>money paid
as earnest, to bind a bargain or to ratify and prove a
sale.</cd></cs></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- <er>Earnest</er>, <er>Pledge</er>.</syn>
<usage>These words are here compared as used in their figurative sense.
<xex>Earnest</xex> is not so strong as <xex>pledge</xex>. An
<xex>earnest</xex>, like first fruits, gives assurance, or at least a
high probability, that more is coming of the same kind; a
<xex>pledge</xex>, like money deposited, affords security and ground of
reliance for the future. Washington gave <xex>earnest</xex> of his
talent as commander by saving his troops after Braddock's defeat; his
fortitude and that of his soldiers during the winter at Valley Forge
might rightly be considered a <xex>pledge</xex> of their ultimate
triumph.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Earnestful</ent>⟦br⟧
